<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900801-0085</DOCNO><DOCID>900801-0085.</DOCID><HL>   U.S. Urges Approval   Of Phone Companies'   Service to New Zealand</HL><DATE>08/01/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   FREST AIT BEL</CO><IN>TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Justice Department recommended allowingAmeritech and Bell Atlantic Corp. to provide long-distanceservice between the U.S. and New Zealand and to ownsatellites and undersea cables for that service.   The New Zealand government, as part of its effort toprivatize state-owned companies, selected Ameritech and BellAtlantic in June to buy the country's phone company, TelecomCorp. of New Zealand, for about $2.46 billion.</LP><TEXT>   The Justice Department made its recommendation to JudgeHarold H. Greene, who oversees the consent decree that brokeup the Bell System in 1984. Among other things, the consentdecree bars the seven regional Baby Bells from providinglong-distance service.   The department concluded that &quot;there is no substantialpossibility&quot; that the two companies will impede competitionin providing telecommunications between the U.S. and NewZealand. The department asked Judge Greene to decide thematter promptly because the transaction goes to closing onSept. 12.   A spokesman for Ameritech said the New Zealand partnershipwas pleased and encouraged that the department &quot;hasrecommended the court act expeditiously to grant the waiver.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>